EXT. PARK BENCH - SUNRISE
A man, MAN, sits contemplatively on a bench. In the distance the sun slowly rises, but he ignores it for a notepad, which lies on his lap. He takes a deep breath and picks up his pen, ready to write.

MAN (v.o.)
Chère Maman... Tu me manques. (Dear Mom... I miss you.)

MAN, unsatisfied, scratches out the words. He exhales and writes again.

MAN (v.o.)
Chère Maman... J'ai commencé à réfléchir au progrès... Je repensais à notre dernière conversation... Et cela m'a rappelé notre voyage en train de Toulouse à... je ne sais plus où... (Dear Mom... I have started thinking about progress... I was thinking about our last conversation... And it reminded me of our train ride from Toulouse to... I can't remember where...)

MAN, still unsatisfied, scratches out the words. He takes a final breath and writes once more.

MAN (v.o.)
Maman... Je repensais à notre dernière conversation... Que voulais-tu dire quand tu as dit : «Il faut entendre le mot avec le son du monde.» Maman, dis-moi...parce que le mot-- (Mom... I was thinking about our last conversation... What did you mean when you said, "One must hear the word with the sound of the world." [Pause] Mother, tell me... because the word--)

Man forgets the word in French. "Beckon"... How does that translate?

WOMAN (o.s.)
Appeler...

MAN does not notice/acknowledge the voice. He continues writing.

MAN
Le mot...beckons...

WOMAN (o.s.)
Appeler...

MAN slowly looks around at Nature, searching for the source. Is it his mother? The wind? He goes back to writing.

MAN
Le mot...beckons...

WOMAN (o.s.)
Appeler...

MAN remembers the word. Appeler. He begins writing.

A WOMAN, 30s, is sitting on a parallel bench across the lookout.

MAN (v.o.)
Le mot m'appelle loin du confort... (The word beckons me away from comfort...)

WOMAN
(softly)
Come here often?

MAN
(surprised)
Huh?

WOMAN
(louder)
Do you come here often?

MAN
Ah... yes. In the mornings, you?

WOMAN
(smiles)
Wouldn't you know if you come here often?

MAN
(smiles back)
Not with certainty.

WOMAN 
(pauses)
Passing through. Duluth. Keokuck. Now... As good a stop as any, wouldn't you say?

MAN
Why?

WOMAN gestures towards the landscape with her eyes. 

MAN
Why are you passing through?

WOMAN prepares for a big anecdote.

MAN
(cuts her off)
What are you reading?

WOMAN
Oh, Pushkin.

WOMAN holds up the book. It's a worn copy of Eugene Onegin.

MAN
In Russian?

WOMAN
No, translation.

MAN
Oh.

MAN returns to his notebook. WOMAN slowly pulls out a folded map.

WOMAN
Would you happen to know the way out?

MAN
Straight down. Take a right at the sycamore by the bend. Then you'll hit the main road.

WOMAN
What does a sycamore look like? 

MAN
If you have gone too far, you'll know.

MAN closes his notebook, stands up. He takes a few steps, then lights a cigarette. 

WOMAN folds her map and returns to her book.

WOMAN
(while reading)
It's not all translatable, you know. But how else would we know of Pushkin?

MAN
(defeated)
Hmm... Feeble meaning is still better than nothing at all. 

A gust of wind blows through the trees. MAN and WOMAN are taken by surprise. 

WOMAN
Is it a poem? 

MAN
Something like that. (Laughs) It doesn't rhyme. 

WOMAN stands up and takes a few steps. She looks into the distance. 

A stronger gust of wind blows through. MAN's sheet of paper flies away. It twists and turns in the air. MAN slowly chases it.

WOMAN
Hah... He has a very rebellious turn of mind...

Slowly, WOMAN follows MAN. MAN picks up the fallen paper.

EXT. WOODS/FOREST - DAYTIME
A young BOY, 7, picks up some soil. He hears his name and turns in its direction. What is its source?

Slowly, he walks. Is he being pulled or is he searching?

EXT. PARK ROAD - MOMENTS LATER
MAN and WOMAN are walking on the road.

WOMAN
(comfortable)
On my way up from Ste. Genevieve, train got delayed...because of another train.... Man behind me gets a call from his wife.... She's angry because surely he is cheating again... Hah...

MAN 
You said you came from Keokuck...

WOMAN
I misspoke...

They walk in silence for a beat.

WOMAN (cont.)
The train stops half a mile too far. He passes her house on the train...to get to her house...

MAN
Feels like fate, no?

WOMAN
I am indifferent to fate.

MAN
A half-mile walk isn't too far, if it takes you home.

WOMAN
Every time I go home, this tiredness overcomes me...

MAN and WOMAN look up. They notice a small beauty. (A tree, a bird...off screen)

EXT. WOODS - MOMENTS LATER
BOY navigates through the woods. He cuts through bushes and trees. He arrives at an opening.

WOMAN (v.o.)
It's so beautiful that you think you discovered it...

MAN (v.o.)
And if we didn't?

WOMAN (v.o.)
But...it feels like the beginning of a process, rather than an end in itself...

MAN (v.o.)
Oh, beauty... [Pause] The blindness to which it gave rise... If only we could see.

WOMAN (v.o.)
What would we see?

MAN (v.o.)
We would see straight away that something is true, and something is false.

EXT. BOLLARD AREA - MOMENTS LATER
MAN and WOMAN weave through a set of bollards.

MAN
Cigarette?

WOMAN
No...

Man lights one more cigarette for himself.

MAN
When do you leave?

WOMAN
Soon.

MAN
Stay another day. See the city.

WOMAN
No...

MAN
What's the hurry?

MAN and WOMAN sit on bollards.

WOMAN
Time... Maybe on a cooler, quieter day, I would have said yes...

MAN blows into the air. You can see his breath... WOMAN smiles.

MAN
It takes two sunrises to know this town...

WOMAN
L’avenir nous prend les bras...or something. (L’avenir nous tend les bras.. she misspeaks the phrase) 

MAN
You can't disappear...

WOMAN
I can't disappear. I'm to be wed in a month. Some altar requires my presence. 

MAN 
Oh, congratulations. Where's your—

WOMAN
Guatemala.

MAN
What for?

WOMAN
Digging wells. 

MAN
Oh, commendable. 

WOMANW 
It's what drew me to him. 

MAN
And how do you manage the separation? 

MAN and WOMAN shift to closer bollards.

WOMAN
I don't think about that. [Pauses] To remember one thing while excluding everything else is a separation in itself. 

MAN
Still it must be... 

WOMAN
From time to time... And from time to time he sends me photos of water systems and children with strange shaped hats.

MAN gets up and walks away. WOMAN follows.

MAN
But you're creating different memories...

WOMAN
All memories are an invention of repression.

They walk in silence.

WOMAN (cont.)
Human consciousness is oriented towards what hasn't arrived... You cannot live without daydreaming...

MAN
I think there is another way...

WOMAN
Those that can dream of The Garden of Eden are-

MAN 
(cuts her off)
Eden is a memory...

WOMAN
To not dream means to die. And it’s never easy to die.

MAN
You cannot live without memory... It's never easy to die.

WOMAN
Feel that?

MAN
What?

WOMAN
A hint of hatred dwells in that belief... [Pause] The heart’s memory eliminates the bad and magnifies the good. The mind's is quite the opposite. Either way, it's catering to first world issues through a first world lens...

MAN
Tell me more.

WOMAN
The past. It's a Bourgeois self-interest... And it likes to draw all other interest into its own failure... 

MAN
Bourgeois?

MAN looks down at his clothes. 

WOMAN
My words poorly portray my thoughts...

MAN
Everything first sneaks in through language. Action comes later... Read me from your book.

WOMAN reads from book. (Insert passage)

MAN
I doubt you ever even notice when the skies change from day to night...

WOMAN
Hah... How can you tell?

MAN
The way you read...

WOMAN puts the book in her jacket pocket...

MAN
A beautiful jacket...

WOMAN
It was my mother's...

MAN
It reeks of genealogy...

MAN (cont.)
The best color for a jacket...and for the leaves...

MAN walks away.

EXT. WOODS - CONTINUOUS
BOY walks through the opening, and sees a bed/manger in the middle of the woods.

He slowly makes his way up to it. He touches the cloth. He gets on. He starts jumping. Slow, then faster.

He starts to turn. Suddenly, he stops. He sees something. Tears well in his eyes.

EXT. LOVER'S LEAP - MOMENTS LATER

MAN and WOMAN sit on a ledge. WOMAN reads from her book. She pauses.

WOMAN 
So you hate translations?

MAN: 
I don't hate them. In fact, I succumb to them. 

WOMAN
But nothing is ever transmitted in its entirety. Always a filtered remainder.

MAN
Ah, so preservation?

WOMAN
*something*

MAN
Language itself is a filtering of its own.

WOMAN
Language is just a mode of communication. 

MAN
Yes, but not poetry. [Pause] Communication transmits what is already known. But what about the unknown? [Pauses] What about the moment when something within the human being becomes too complete, too charged, too coherent to remain unexpressed... and therefore must take shape in the world.

WOMAN
As in... a becoming?

MAN pauses. 

MAN
A poem doesn't tell you that something is being felt; it makes you feel that something was felt. Expression is its arrival. Not its becoming.

WOMAN
Beauty is futural in action. 

MAN
It is elegaic in substance.

They pause.

MAN
So can it be received? Or perceived?

WOMAN
Something beautiful isn't a prisoner of perception. It's the master of it. 

MAN
As in reorientation?

WOMAN
Yes, and in that sense, beauty is simply presence. 

MAN
And what about the presence of absence? I find that incredibly beautiful.

WOMAN
You must have your reasons.

MAN chuckles.

WOMAN
Some want time measured out. Some want it felt.

They sit in silence at a deadlock.

The river, trees, skies, open field, are all listening in. MAN and WOMAN are one with nature.

WOMAN
How old are the trees? The river?

MAN
And the wind?

WOMAN
It's hard to say.

MAN
It's hard to know.

EXT. WOODS - CONTINUOUS
WOMAN, now old, stands in the forest. She looks somberly into the distance.